102
00:05:06,960 --> 00:05:09,120
So let's start off with
some vocab right now.

103
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:11,880
So first, we have
the logical layer.

104
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:14,820
This enables the user to join
the data using relationships

105
00:05:14,820 --> 00:05:16,140
otherwise known as noodles.

106
00:05:16,140 --> 00:05:20,160
So this right here is the
noodle, if you remember.

107
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:24,645
And this right here
is the logical layer.

108
00:05:29,260 --> 00:05:31,430
And we'll explain what
our relationships.

109
00:05:31,430 --> 00:05:33,460
So in Tableau,
relationships are a way

110
00:05:33,460 --> 00:05:37,130
to connect tables within a data
source based on common fields.

111
00:05:37,130 --> 00:05:39,430
So relationships are
distinct from joins,

112
00:05:39,430 --> 00:05:41,410
and they are
particularly useful when

113
00:05:41,410 --> 00:05:44,980
dealing with data that comes
from different databases or data

114
00:05:44,980 --> 00:05:45,760
sources.

115
00:05:45,760 --> 00:05:48,670
Relationships allow you to
establish logical connections

116
00:05:48,670 --> 00:05:51,820
between tables without
physically combining the tables

117
00:05:51,820 --> 00:05:55,240
into a single table,
which is what joint does

118
00:05:55,240 --> 00:05:57,250
or what a join does.

119
00:05:57,250 --> 00:06:03,890
And the way to do this is
to combine the primary key

120
00:06:03,890 --> 00:06:06,830
of one table and the table--

121
00:06:06,830 --> 00:06:09,350
and the other table that
contains the foreign key.

122
00:06:09,350 --> 00:06:12,260
So the primary key is uniquely--

123
00:06:12,260 --> 00:06:15,020
or the primary key uniquely
identifies each record

124
00:06:15,020 --> 00:06:18,170
in the primary table, while the
foreign key in the related table

125
00:06:18,170 --> 00:06:20,870
links back to the primary key.

126
00:06:20,870 --> 00:06:22,700
So if the data source--

127
00:06:22,700 --> 00:06:24,800
if a data sources have
different field names,

128
00:06:24,800 --> 00:06:29,070
Tableau will ask the user to
define the matching columns.

129
00:06:29,070 --> 00:06:31,670
So if we look here, if we
click on a noodle here,

130
00:06:31,670 --> 00:06:34,470
you can see the relationship
that's happening here.

131
00:06:34,470 --> 00:06:38,240
So we're doing-- we're
connecting region.

132
00:06:38,240 --> 00:06:42,420
It's equal to region on this--

133
00:06:42,420 --> 00:06:45,990
on this relationship right here.

134
00:06:45,990 --> 00:06:49,420
And then sometimes it
does this automatically,

135
00:06:49,420 --> 00:06:53,200
but you might want to always
check just in case to see

136
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:54,700
that if it did it correctly.

137
00:06:54,700 --> 00:06:58,120
And sometimes it'll ask
you to do it manually too.

138
00:06:58,120 --> 00:07:00,030
So yeah.

139
00:07:00,030 --> 00:07:01,540
Let's move on.

140
00:07:01,540 --> 00:07:03,300
So let's do more vocabulary.

141
00:07:03,300 --> 00:07:05,610
Now, we have the
physical layer, which

142
00:07:05,610 --> 00:07:07,920
is regarded as a
sub logical layer.

143
00:07:07,920 --> 00:07:12,390
In order to access it, you need
a double click a logical table.

144
00:07:12,390 --> 00:07:15,960
In the physical layer, you
are able to use joins, unions

145
00:07:15,960 --> 00:07:18,930
by dragging another table
into blank space for joins

146
00:07:18,930 --> 00:07:22,200
and on top of the
table for unions.

147
00:07:22,200 --> 00:07:25,890
So you know it is a join if
it creates one of these Venn

148
00:07:25,890 --> 00:07:28,980
diagrams, and then it's a
union if it looks like it's

149
00:07:28,980 --> 00:07:31,080
kind of stacked on each other.

150
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:34,020
And we'll touch on that again.

151
00:07:34,020 --> 00:07:35,490
So what are joins?

152
00:07:35,490 --> 00:07:39,090
Joins in Tableau combine
fields from different tables

153
00:07:39,090 --> 00:07:42,740
based on related column
on a related column.

154
00:07:42,740 --> 00:07:44,870
Joins can be done in
the physical layer

155
00:07:44,870 --> 00:07:47,990
by double clicking
on the logical table.

156
00:07:47,990 --> 00:07:50,600
So the different types of
joins that Tableau supports,

157
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:53,120
we have, first off,
the inner join,

158
00:07:53,120 --> 00:07:56,010
which retains only the matching
records from both tables.

159
00:07:56,010 --> 00:07:58,400
So that'll be this
one right here.

160
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,050
Then we have our
left join, which

161
00:08:00,050 --> 00:08:03,980
retains all records from
the left table and matching

162
00:08:03,980 --> 00:08:05,808
records from the right table.

163
00:08:05,808 --> 00:08:07,100
That'll be this one right here.

164
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:09,050
Then it's the opposite
for right join.

165
00:08:09,050 --> 00:08:11,990
So it will retain all
records from the right table

166
00:08:11,990 --> 00:08:14,840
and matching records
from the left table.

167
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:17,810
And then for a full outer join,
when you use a full outer join,

168
00:08:17,810 --> 00:08:20,720
the result is a table
that contains all values

169
00:08:20,720 --> 00:08:22,580
from both tables.

170
00:08:22,580 --> 00:08:25,520
And on joins create
a horizontal data

171
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:28,610
combination, which creates
like a wider table.

172
00:08:28,610 --> 00:08:33,020
And let's show you
guys right here then.

173
00:08:33,020 --> 00:08:37,990
So let's just click on
the orders right here.

174
00:08:37,990 --> 00:08:38,690
All righty.

175
00:08:38,690 --> 00:08:39,710
So we double click.

176
00:08:39,710 --> 00:08:44,179
And now, this is our logical
or our physical layer.

177
00:08:44,179 --> 00:08:48,120
And let's just drag
people, for example.

178
00:08:48,120 --> 00:08:50,660
So if you highlight
over it, you can see,

179
00:08:50,660 --> 00:08:55,970
it says drag union or
drag table to union.

180
00:08:55,970 --> 00:08:59,570
And then if you hover-- if
you hover it over here, like

181
00:08:59,570 --> 00:09:04,790
in the blank space and just
drop it, it'll create the join,

182
00:09:04,790 --> 00:09:05,850
the inner join here.

183
00:09:05,850 --> 00:09:08,730
And if you click on
the Venn diagram,

184
00:09:08,730 --> 00:09:11,790
it will give you the different
options of what you want to do.

185
00:09:11,790 --> 00:09:14,370
So for example, we have
region equal to region here.

186
00:09:16,920 --> 00:09:18,110
So let's get rid of it.

187
00:09:18,110 --> 00:09:19,790
Oops.

188
00:09:19,790 --> 00:09:20,600
All right.

189
00:09:20,600 --> 00:09:21,800
Let's get rid of this.

190
00:09:24,470 --> 00:09:24,970
All right.

191
00:09:24,970 --> 00:09:27,360
Actually.

192
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:29,410
Yeah, that's fine.

193
00:09:29,410 --> 00:09:30,820
Awesome.

194
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:32,740
So now, what are unions?

195
00:09:32,740 --> 00:09:35,890
Unions is a way to
append the two data

196
00:09:35,890 --> 00:09:38,800
connections with the matching
number of columns and data

197
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:39,730
types.

198
00:09:39,730 --> 00:09:42,130
So this happens in
the physical layer

199
00:09:42,130 --> 00:09:44,260
by double clicking
a logical table.

200
00:09:44,260 --> 00:09:47,200
Unions are commonly used
when you have a data

201
00:09:47,200 --> 00:09:49,160
split across multiple tables.

202
00:09:49,160 --> 00:09:51,860
So perhaps the data is
distributed over time.

203
00:09:51,860 --> 00:09:55,540
So monthly or yearly
tables as an example there.

204
00:09:55,540 --> 00:09:58,690
And unlike joins,
unions vertically

205
00:09:58,690 --> 00:10:03,830
stack the records from each
table, creating a longer table.

206
00:10:03,830 --> 00:10:06,440
And we'll show you
that right here.

207
00:10:06,440 --> 00:10:08,000
Let's see.

208
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,170
So as I mentioned here,
you can just drop it here.

209
00:10:12,170 --> 00:10:15,080
And it has-- it creates like a
vertical stack here, which makes

210
00:10:15,080 --> 00:10:16,550
it the table a lot longer.

211
00:10:19,470 --> 00:10:22,485
And then if you want to edit it,
you just click this down arrow,

212
00:10:22,485 --> 00:10:23,860
or I believe you
can right click.

213
00:10:23,860 --> 00:10:26,430
Yeah, you can right click
or click the down arrow.

214
00:10:26,430 --> 00:10:28,140
Edit union.

215
00:10:28,140 --> 00:10:30,120
And then let's get
rid of returns.

216
00:10:34,310 --> 00:10:35,090
Awesome.

217
00:10:41,050 --> 00:10:44,000
So now, which connection
should you use?

218
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,720
So for relationships, you
can use a relationship

219
00:10:46,720 --> 00:10:49,270
when the data is connected
through some common field.

220
00:10:49,270 --> 00:10:52,240
And Tableau automatically
creates them

221
00:10:52,240 --> 00:10:55,000
or creates the appropriate
joins unless the data field

222
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:55,910
name is different.

223
00:10:55,910 --> 00:10:58,120
So that's when you'll
have to do it manually.

224
00:10:58,120 --> 00:11:02,410
And joins use-- or I guess use
joins when combining fields

225
00:11:02,410 --> 00:11:04,840
horizontally from different
tables, especially

226
00:11:04,840 --> 00:11:10,260
when working with data from
distinct sources or databases.

227
00:11:10,260 --> 00:11:15,570
And as for unions, use unions
when stacking records vertically

228
00:11:15,570 --> 00:11:17,730
from tables with
matching structures,

229
00:11:17,730 --> 00:11:20,610
such as combining time
series data or data

230
00:11:20,610 --> 00:11:22,440
sets with similar formats.

231
00:11:27,220 --> 00:11:27,720
Awesome.

232
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:30,120
And now, bringing data in.

233
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:32,110
So this is very important.

234
00:11:32,110 --> 00:11:33,930
So in Tableau there,
I believe there

235
00:11:33,930 --> 00:11:37,890
are two main ways-- there
are two main ways to bring

236
00:11:37,890 --> 00:11:41,220
in and connect to data,
through the data source tab

237
00:11:41,220 --> 00:11:45,390
and directly in a
worksheet on the Data tab.

238
00:11:45,390 --> 00:11:49,140
So in the data source
tab, you bring in data

239
00:11:49,140 --> 00:11:54,360
by clicking the add button
under the connections, which

240
00:11:54,360 --> 00:11:55,860
is top left.

241
00:11:55,860 --> 00:11:58,560
We use this if we want to
connect our new data set

242
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:02,340
with the old data set using
different types of connections

243
00:12:02,340 --> 00:12:05,960
we talked about in the
previous slide here.

244
00:12:05,960 --> 00:12:08,200
And as for worksheets,
you bring in data

245
00:12:08,200 --> 00:12:10,930
in the worksheet by clicking
the Data tab at the top,

246
00:12:10,930 --> 00:12:14,080
and then clicking
on new data source.

247
00:12:14,080 --> 00:12:16,990
We use this if we
don't want our data,

248
00:12:16,990 --> 00:12:21,090
the new data set, to
connect to the old data set.

249
00:12:21,090 --> 00:12:23,210
So it'll be like
working with two--

250
00:12:23,210 --> 00:12:27,980
for example, two different
Excel files and one worksheet

251
00:12:27,980 --> 00:12:30,640
or per worksheet.

252
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:32,710
And from there, you can--

253
00:12:32,710 --> 00:12:37,770
without them-- without them
being related in any way.

